Dynamic reports with RMarkdown

Leo Hardtke & Andrew Ferris
04-July-2017

Dynamic documents

  • Documents that include include formatted text, code, and the results of the analysis performed.

  • Different to WYSIWYG. Some problems:

    • Changes in input files?
    • Repetitive tasks?
    • How to reproduce?

  • Why should you use dynamic reports?

    • great way to collaborate with colleagues. (GIT)
    • keep your research organized.
    • reproducible research.
    • Stable format. Not locked into vendors

How to produce dynamic reports in R

  • write a plain text file with formatting in markdown including the code
  • knitr executes all of the code chunks and creates a new markdown document which includes the code and it’s output.
  • pandoc which is responsible for creating the report in its finished format (e.g. html, pdf, odt, doc, etc).
  • rmarkdown packages makes it extremely simple by encapsulating all of the above processing into a single function.

Markdown

  • lightweight markup language
  • ordinary text, plus signs which indicate how to change the formatting or meaning of the text -key design goal: readability, without looking like it has been marked up with tags (html).
  • The basic Markdown syntax is really intuitive and easy to learn.

Markdown

A few examples:

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Front-matters

Initial chunk of text containing some properties

  • title
  • author
  • date
  • output format
---
title: "Learning R Markdown"
author: "John Doe"
date: "July 04, 2017"
output: html_document
---

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Front-matters

  • output: define the output format (html, pdf, odt, doc or rtf)
  • **toc: true** to include a table of contents. Set the depth with toc_depth: 2
  • number_sections: true add numbering to section headers
  • css: styles.css if working with html, to change the stylesheet.
  • latex options if working on a pdf, you can customize most aspects of the LaTeX template. Documentation here.

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Front-matters

  • fig_width: fig_height: can be used to control the default figure width and height (6 x 4.5 is used by default)
  • fig_caption: to render figures with captions (this is false by default).

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Code

The real point of rmarkdown is that it lets you include and run your code.

  • To distinguish code from text, R Markdown uses back-ticks.
  • The code can be included in two varieties, code chunks and inline code.

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Code

Inline code

Code output can be incorporated into the text, using inline code. Inline code should be wrapped with one back-ticks and will be replaced by its output when rendered. For example: r 1+1, will be replaced by 2.

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Code

Code chunk

Wrap code with three back-ticks followed by {r name, option=value}

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Code

Code chunk options

Output can be customized with knitr options, arguments set in the {} of a chunk header

  • include = FALSE prevents code and results from appearing in the finished file.Code in the chunk and the results can be used by other chunks.
  • echo = FALSE prevents code, but not the results from appearing in the finished file. This is a useful way to embed figures.
  • message = FALSE prevents messages that are generated by code from appearing in the finished file.

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Code

Code chunk options

  • warning = FALSE prevents warnings that are generated by code from appearing in the finished.
  • fig.cap = “…” adds a caption to graphical results.
  • cache = TRUE If document rendering becomes time consuming due to long computations you can use knitr caching to improve performance.

Parts of a rmarkdown document

Code

Global code chunk options

Options that apply to every chunk, can be added by calling knitr::opts_chunk$set in your first code chunk. Knitr will treat each option that you pass to knitr::opts_chunk$set as a global default that can be overwritten in individual chunk headers.

For example:

  • knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, cache=TRUE)

Best practice tips

  • Self contained, so you need to load data and code in the document.

  • Load the libraries and datasets in a code-chunk at the beginning of your document. (with include=FALSE ?)

  • Avoid absolute paths.

  • Keep all of the data within one branch of your file system.

  • Include your “session info” in your document, preferably at the bottom.

  • If you do any sort of simulation in the document, consider adding a call to set.seed in the first code chunk

Working with figures:

Figures are very easy to include. If a code chunk produces a figure, the figure will be automatically produced and inserted into the final document.

ggplot(data=rainfall) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x=rainfall, fill=name),binwidth = 20, show.legend = F)

Working with tables:

Kable

If you want to render a table, the simplest approach is to use the kable() function in the knitr package.

Working with tables:

Kable

Input: matrix or data frame Some useful options:

  • Set the maximum number of digits with the digit parameter
  • whether or not include row and column names (row.names and col.names)
  • use 'c', 'l', 'r' to align rows.

Working with tables:

Pander

For a finer control on the output format (e.g. style, caption, cell highlighting, cell alignment, width), use the pander().

Working with tables:

Pander

Some options: justification: alignment of the cells (left, right or center/centre) split.table: to define how many characters before splitting tables (Default=80) split.cell: how many characters in a cell before splitting a new line. (Default=30). Individual, vector, relative vector.
